<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1898-06-29T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1898-06-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="750" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d750">
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Campbell</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Day</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Consulate of the United States</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Port Louis, Mauritius</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1898-06-29"><hi rend="italic">June
                                        29, 1898</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 53.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The inclosed proclamations,<note n="2" xml:id="d750fn2">Not printed. The proclamation is in the same terms,
                                mutatis mutandis, as that of Great Britain, see <ref target="#pg_865">page 865</ref>.</note> No. 10 and No. 11, were
                            published on the dates affixed to the newspaper clippings, inclosure No.
                            3. (April 23 and 26, respectively.)</p>
                        <p rend="center">* * * * * * *</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John P. Campbell</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">United States Consul.</hi></signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>